## 2. Conceptual hierarchy

```
PRD                      (01-planning/prd/)         — product initiative
  └─ Epic                (01-planning/epics/)       — large deliverable; stories as bullets in ## Stories
       └─ Spec           (04-specs/<feature>/)      — SDD trio for feature
            ├─ requirements.md   (testable EARS)
            ├─ design.md         (technical design)
            └─ tasks.md          (executable task list)
                 └─ Task          — references REQ-NNN and, if API, contract in 02-architecture/api/
```

In parallel:
- **Milestone** (`01-planning/milestones/`) groups epics by delivery date.
- **Sprint** (recorded in SQLite, no folder) groups tasks by time cycle.
- **ADR** (`02-architecture/adr/`) captures irreversible or expensive-to-revert architectural decisions.

---

## 3. Story vs. requirement boundary (critical — do not confuse)

| Artifact | Location | Format | Author | Answers |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Story** | Bullet in `01-planning/epics/<slug>.md` (section `## Stories`) | *"As X, I want Y, so that Z"* | Product | **WHAT + FOR WHOM** |
| **Requirement** | `04-specs/<feature>/requirements.md` (REQ-NNN) | EARS: `WHEN <trigger> THE SYSTEM SHALL <behavior>` | Tech | **HOW TO TEST** |

One story may become multiple specs; one spec contains multiple requirements; one requirement becomes one or more tasks. **Stories are not skills or separate files** — they live as bullets within the epic.

